1
00:00:04,651 --> 00:00:09,155
The prosecution presented three grounds
for naming Mr. Serizawa as the culprit.

2
00:00:09,239 --> 00:00:11,449
The first was motive.

3
00:00:11,533 --> 00:00:17,831
They claimed that Serizawa
was stalking the first victim, Yui Sato.

4
00:00:17,914 --> 00:00:22,794
Serizawa admits that he contacted Sato
by phone and letters,

5
00:00:22,877 --> 00:00:24,462
but he denies the murder.

6
00:00:24,546 --> 00:00:26,798
The second was the murder weapon.

7
00:00:26,881 --> 00:00:31,719
It was judged the marks could match
a belt he possessed.

8
00:00:31,803 --> 00:00:34,097
The third was the DNA test.

9
00:00:34,180 --> 00:00:36,266
In order to file a request for a retrial,

10
00:00:36,349 --> 00:00:39,144
we need to overturn these grounds.

11
00:00:39,227 --> 00:00:40,145
However,

12
00:00:40,728 --> 00:00:43,898
it might be difficult
with just these documents.

13
00:00:43,982 --> 00:00:47,735
Because your mentor
was in charge of these reports,

14
00:00:47,819 --> 00:00:50,071
they must be legit, right?

15
00:00:51,239 --> 00:00:52,323
Yes.

16
00:01:05,461 --> 00:01:06,629
What happened?

17
00:01:09,465 --> 00:01:11,843
It's a breaking news report
of an execution.

18
00:01:18,850 --> 00:01:24,230
<i>Today, one death row inmate</i>
<i>has been executed.</i>

19
00:01:24,856 --> 00:01:29,068
<i>It was an extremely brutal crime in which</i>
<i>multiple precious lives were taken</i>

20
00:01:29,152 --> 00:01:31,446
<i>for entirely selfish reasons.</i>

21
00:01:32,030 --> 00:01:33,031
<i>In the end,</i>

22
00:01:33,114 --> 00:01:37,285
<i>after careful deliberation,</i>
<i>it was decided he would be executed.</i>

23
00:01:39,746 --> 00:01:40,997
It's Akiko.

24
00:01:42,874 --> 00:01:44,667
Hello, this is Kiryu.

25
00:01:51,132 --> 00:01:52,091
Yes.

26
00:02:05,355 --> 00:02:06,856
The one who was executed

27
00:02:07,732 --> 00:02:09,609
was not Serizawa.

28
00:02:13,238 --> 00:02:14,656
That's good.

29
00:02:20,578 --> 00:02:21,537
It wasn't me today.

30
00:02:22,372 --> 00:02:25,667
Don't worry. We will save you.

31
00:02:27,752 --> 00:02:28,878
It wasn't me today.

32
00:02:33,007 --> 00:02:34,175
It wasn't me.

33
00:02:49,524 --> 00:02:52,819
Those documents Professor Kujo had
on the Shiramine case…

34
00:02:53,403 --> 00:02:56,531
Could you look for them one more time?

35
00:03:05,164 --> 00:03:07,208
If it's the documents you want,

36
00:03:07,291 --> 00:03:08,584
I found them.

37
00:03:11,087 --> 00:03:12,046
But…

38
00:03:14,132 --> 00:03:15,383
I threw them away.

39
00:03:17,719 --> 00:03:19,012
Could you leave?

40
00:03:20,013 --> 00:03:21,472
Don't ever come back again.

41
00:03:24,350 --> 00:03:25,476
<i>Tomorrow,</i>

42
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:27,478
we're going to Shiramine.

43
00:03:28,980 --> 00:03:33,693
What was the town of Shiramine like
at the time?

44
00:03:36,154 --> 00:03:41,284
Everyone was exhausted from the anxiety
of when the next murder might happen.

45
00:03:44,078 --> 00:03:46,622
I heard there was even a police officer

46
00:03:46,706 --> 00:03:49,709
who committed suicide due to the stress
of the investigation.

47
00:03:53,046 --> 00:03:54,464
In the midst of all that,

48
00:03:55,298 --> 00:03:57,884
Shinichi suddenly got arrested.

49
00:03:59,594 --> 00:04:01,471
But Shinichi always said it.

50
00:04:02,805 --> 00:04:05,266
He said he definitely didn't do it.

51
00:04:08,644 --> 00:04:12,899
I've believed him this entire time.

52
00:04:20,323 --> 00:04:21,824
But recently,

53
00:04:22,867 --> 00:04:24,911
I find myself thinking sometimes

54
00:04:27,413 --> 00:04:28,998
that maybe

55
00:04:29,999 --> 00:04:31,918
we might not make it in time anymore.

56
00:04:39,092 --> 00:04:40,760
<i>How long will I have to wait?</i>

57
00:04:40,843 --> 00:04:43,096
Return my daughter, quickly!

58
00:04:43,805 --> 00:04:47,350
<i>Yukie is a victim of a serial murder case.</i>

59
00:04:47,433 --> 00:04:49,685
We need to investigate carefully.

60
00:04:50,395 --> 00:04:52,355
So what have you found out?

61
00:04:52,438 --> 00:04:54,774
You can catch the killer now, right?

62
00:04:55,400 --> 00:04:59,278
No traces connecting to the killer
have been found.

63
00:05:00,196 --> 00:05:01,823
They haven't been found?

64
00:05:02,907 --> 00:05:05,576
Then what did you perform the autopsy for?

65
00:05:10,331 --> 00:05:11,666
I am terribly sorry.

66
00:05:12,708 --> 00:05:15,711
Anyway,
please let me take my daughter home.

67
00:05:17,839 --> 00:05:20,967
The test results
will be ready by tomorrow,

68
00:05:21,676 --> 00:05:25,513
so she will be returned to her family.

69
00:05:26,013 --> 00:05:27,265
Please wait

70
00:05:28,224 --> 00:05:29,600
just a little longer.

71
00:05:29,684 --> 00:05:32,228
Yukie Morishita's
judicial autopsy results.

72
00:05:32,311 --> 00:05:34,230
I got what they have as of right now.

73
00:05:34,313 --> 00:05:35,898
Thank you very much.

74
00:05:41,112 --> 00:05:42,321
This wound…

75
00:05:43,739 --> 00:05:45,616
It's a little strange.

76
00:05:46,284 --> 00:05:47,285
Strange?

77
00:05:48,327 --> 00:05:50,204
According to the report,

78
00:05:50,288 --> 00:05:55,001
the injuries to the cheek and lips
could be from when she fell down.

79
00:05:56,627 --> 00:05:58,379
How is that weird?

80
00:05:58,462 --> 00:05:59,922
Depending on the situation,

81
00:06:00,006 --> 00:06:02,842
the contents of the report would add up.

82
00:06:03,509 --> 00:06:04,510
However,

83
00:06:04,594 --> 00:06:10,224
I feel like something's off
with how the wounds were made.

84
00:06:16,022 --> 00:06:19,192
Morishita's body
is still at the university, isn't it?

85
00:06:20,234 --> 00:06:23,696
Would it be possible
to let me examine the body?

86
00:06:25,990 --> 00:06:28,284
You mean perform an autopsy once more?

87
00:06:28,367 --> 00:06:29,577
Yes.

88
00:06:32,914 --> 00:06:35,458
Judging by her father's state,

89
00:06:37,001 --> 00:06:38,586
I think it will be difficult.

90
00:06:40,546 --> 00:06:44,884
The documents Professor Kujo had
have already been disposed of.

91
00:06:46,552 --> 00:06:48,554
<i>Ms. Morishita's body</i>

92
00:06:48,638 --> 00:06:52,850
might be the only clue
to clear Mr. Serizawa's false accusation.

93
00:07:17,458 --> 00:07:20,836
<i>It has been 15 years</i>
<i>since Yui passed away.</i>

94
00:07:21,587 --> 00:07:22,838
The other day,

95
00:07:22,922 --> 00:07:27,176
I saw on the news
that the killer's family is…

96
00:07:29,220 --> 00:07:30,680
claiming his innocence.

97
00:07:33,474 --> 00:07:34,684
Your daughter

98
00:07:35,476 --> 00:07:38,854
was being stalked by Serizawa, right?

99
00:07:39,897 --> 00:07:40,982
That's right.

100
00:07:41,983 --> 00:07:44,402
She refused him,
because she had a boyfriend.

101
00:07:45,403 --> 00:07:47,530
Even so, he wouldn't give up.

102
00:07:49,865 --> 00:07:51,033
I told her

103
00:07:51,742 --> 00:07:54,036
we should go to the police.

104
00:07:56,622 --> 00:07:57,915
But Yui said

105
00:07:59,292 --> 00:08:01,877
there was no need to worry that much.

106
00:08:05,339 --> 00:08:06,340
Um,

107
00:08:07,508 --> 00:08:09,760
her boyfriend at the time…

108
00:08:10,261 --> 00:08:12,847
Does he still live nearby?

109
00:08:14,932 --> 00:08:17,351
He passed away.

110
00:08:18,811 --> 00:08:19,812
What?

111
00:08:20,396 --> 00:08:22,398
He followed Yui.

112
00:08:23,816 --> 00:08:25,860
He committed suicide.

113
00:08:29,113 --> 00:08:30,489
I should have…

114
00:08:33,659 --> 00:08:36,746
gone to the police,
even if she didn't want to.

115
00:08:42,960 --> 00:08:46,797
I will absolutely never forgive Serizawa

116
00:08:47,965 --> 00:08:49,842
for taking Yui away from me.

117
00:08:58,809 --> 00:09:01,520
So I told my boss.

118
00:09:02,229 --> 00:09:03,606
"It doesn't add up!"

119
00:09:03,689 --> 00:09:05,232
Wow, awesome.

120
00:09:05,316 --> 00:09:06,317
Right?

121
00:09:06,400 --> 00:09:08,611
I just can't ignore those things,
you know?

122
00:09:08,694 --> 00:09:09,987
Strange things are--

123
00:09:10,071 --> 00:09:12,114
Hey, it's about that time, isn't it?

124
00:09:12,198 --> 00:09:14,158
Shall we head home then?

125
00:09:15,534 --> 00:09:17,745
What are you saying?
On to the next spot!

126
00:09:17,828 --> 00:09:18,913
What?

127
00:09:18,996 --> 00:09:21,582
-Excuse me! Bill please.
-Okay.

128
00:09:21,666 --> 00:09:23,959
We need Dr. Honda now more than ever.

129
00:09:24,043 --> 00:09:26,170
The burden is too heavy for just us!

130
00:09:26,253 --> 00:09:27,129
We can't!

131
00:09:27,213 --> 00:09:31,425
He left yesterday to help with autopsies
at Kyomei University, so he's busy.

132
00:09:40,393 --> 00:09:41,310
Mr. Morishita.

133
00:09:44,313 --> 00:09:46,190
Do you have a moment?

134
00:09:46,899 --> 00:09:48,192
What is it?

135
00:09:49,652 --> 00:09:51,696
I had a forensic scientist

136
00:09:51,779 --> 00:09:55,658
from an organization called MEJ
look at Yukie's autopsy results.

137
00:09:55,741 --> 00:09:56,992
That doctor said

138
00:09:57,076 --> 00:10:00,579
there is something strange
with the wounds on Yukie's face.

139
00:10:05,710 --> 00:10:07,211
Could you let us

140
00:10:08,462 --> 00:10:12,216
examine Yukie's body just one more time?

141
00:10:14,510 --> 00:10:17,680
You mean
you want to perform another autopsy?

142
00:10:21,308 --> 00:10:22,143
Yes.

143
00:10:26,188 --> 00:10:28,023
Don't mess with me!

144
00:10:29,024 --> 00:10:30,860
Yukie was murdered,

145
00:10:30,943 --> 00:10:32,528
and even autopsied.

146
00:10:33,529 --> 00:10:36,741
Are you telling me
to hurt that child again?

147
00:10:37,950 --> 00:10:41,328
I understand your feelings very well.

148
00:10:43,789 --> 00:10:45,249
But that doctor

149
00:10:46,083 --> 00:10:50,004
has found so many small contradictions
left on bodies

150
00:10:50,087 --> 00:10:53,591
that nobody else had noticed.

151
00:10:55,092 --> 00:10:57,678
He has always uncovered the truth.

152
00:10:58,846 --> 00:11:00,055
He will…

153
00:11:01,474 --> 00:11:06,520
find the contradiction
left behind by Yukie for us.

154
00:11:18,616 --> 00:11:19,617
Please…

155
00:11:21,327 --> 00:11:22,620
I beg you.

156
00:11:24,580 --> 00:11:29,376
I don't want there to be any other
victims like Yukie ever again.

157
00:11:37,510 --> 00:11:40,638
I am not going to change
the time for her wake.

158
00:11:45,768 --> 00:11:47,561
Make sure to return her

159
00:11:48,354 --> 00:11:50,189
by 6:00 p.m. tonight.

160
00:12:00,574 --> 00:12:01,992
Thank you very much.

161
00:12:05,829 --> 00:12:07,790
By 6:00 p.m.?

162
00:12:07,873 --> 00:12:10,876
Taking into account
the time to deliver the body back,

163
00:12:10,960 --> 00:12:13,212
we only have about two hours left.

164
00:12:14,755 --> 00:12:15,798
Will we make it?

165
00:12:17,675 --> 00:12:19,969
We just have to do what we can.

166
00:12:20,052 --> 00:12:21,053
Let's hurry.

167
00:12:21,136 --> 00:12:22,137
Yes.

168
00:12:22,721 --> 00:12:23,847
I will help too.

169
00:12:49,915 --> 00:12:51,625
What are you all doing here?

170
00:12:52,751 --> 00:12:55,713
I was at Kyomei University today
to help them out.

171
00:12:56,839 --> 00:13:01,260
I happened to hear Ms. Dojima
talking to the bereaved father.

172
00:13:06,098 --> 00:13:07,683
I don't know all the details,

173
00:13:08,601 --> 00:13:11,103
but you have little time
for the autopsy, right?

174
00:13:12,521 --> 00:13:15,649
So, I thought it would be better
to have as many people as possible,

175
00:13:15,733 --> 00:13:17,735
so I hurried and got everyone together.

176
00:13:18,527 --> 00:13:22,698
I also managed to leave early somehow.

177
00:13:25,284 --> 00:13:30,039
I don't know the details of why you
are staying at MEJ, Dr. Masumi.

178
00:13:31,915 --> 00:13:32,750
But,

179
00:13:33,417 --> 00:13:36,670
I understand that this autopsy
is not just an ordinary autopsy.

180
00:13:36,754 --> 00:13:39,757
Please let us help too.

181
00:13:40,257 --> 00:13:42,468
We want to help you, Dr. Masumi.

182
00:13:48,766 --> 00:13:50,059
Thank you very much.

183
00:13:52,770 --> 00:13:55,397
Well, we don't have much time.

184
00:13:55,981 --> 00:13:57,107
Shall we get to it?

185
00:13:57,191 --> 00:13:58,192
-Yes.
-Yes.

186
00:14:10,746 --> 00:14:13,707
After checking the wounds
on the left cheek and lips,

187
00:14:13,791 --> 00:14:16,460
we found out what Dr. Masumi
thought was strange.

188
00:14:17,086 --> 00:14:19,213
The positions of the wounds are off.

189
00:14:20,047 --> 00:14:20,881
Off?

190
00:14:20,965 --> 00:14:23,884
In the report,
the wounds on the left cheek and lips

191
00:14:23,968 --> 00:14:26,387
are described as beind caused
from falling down.

192
00:14:26,470 --> 00:14:30,265
The wounds on Yukie's body
were concentrated on the left side.

193
00:14:30,349 --> 00:14:33,686
It is natural to think
she fell on her left side.

194
00:14:33,769 --> 00:14:34,603
But,

195
00:14:34,687 --> 00:14:37,189
only the wound on the lip
is closer to the front.

196
00:14:37,272 --> 00:14:39,191
If she fell to the ground
with her left side down,

197
00:14:39,274 --> 00:14:40,985
it would be difficult
to get a wound there.

198
00:14:41,568 --> 00:14:42,778
So,

199
00:14:42,861 --> 00:14:45,322
we tried re-examining
the inside of the mouth once more.

200
00:14:45,406 --> 00:14:47,366
There was bleeding inside the oral cavity,

201
00:14:47,449 --> 00:14:49,368
and not only was there a wound on the lip,

202
00:14:49,451 --> 00:14:52,037
but the upper left canine tooth
was slightly chipped.

203
00:14:52,121 --> 00:14:54,331
Judging from the condition
of the cross-section,

204
00:14:54,415 --> 00:14:56,750
the tooth was chipped very recently.

205
00:14:57,334 --> 00:14:58,669
In other words,

206
00:14:59,253 --> 00:15:02,798
it means there is a possibility
that Yukie bit the culprit.

207
00:15:04,508 --> 00:15:05,592
What?

208
00:15:07,219 --> 00:15:08,429
In that case,

209
00:15:08,512 --> 00:15:11,098
the blood adhering inside the oral cavity

210
00:15:11,181 --> 00:15:15,686
would be a mixture of Yukie's
and the culprit's.

211
00:15:15,769 --> 00:15:18,814
If we do a DNA test on this blood,

212
00:15:19,690 --> 00:15:22,901
we might be able to identify the culprit.

213
00:15:27,531 --> 00:15:29,616
As a result of the DNA test,

214
00:15:29,700 --> 00:15:32,703
a man named Koji Uchiyama has surfaced.

215
00:15:33,579 --> 00:15:37,583
Uchiyama was arrested in 2015
on charges of injury, served time,

216
00:15:37,666 --> 00:15:39,460
and was released at the end of last year.

217
00:15:39,543 --> 00:15:41,795
The timing of Uchiyama's release

218
00:15:41,879 --> 00:15:44,631
overlaps with
when the serial killings began.

219
00:15:44,715 --> 00:15:47,885
Furthermore, it seems Uchiyama
used to be an informant

220
00:15:47,968 --> 00:15:50,304
who leaked underworld information
to the police.

221
00:15:51,513 --> 00:15:55,142
It wouldn't be surprising if he knew
the police's investigative methods.

222
00:15:55,225 --> 00:15:59,730
That's why absolutely no evidence
came up in the investigation until now.

223
00:16:32,554 --> 00:16:33,847
Stop right there!

224
00:16:41,271 --> 00:16:43,065
You smell nice, ma'am.

225
00:16:45,984 --> 00:16:47,444
Secured him!

226
00:16:48,028 --> 00:16:51,782
We couldn't find any direct evidence
at Uchiyama's home.

227
00:16:51,865 --> 00:16:56,870
At this rate, it may be difficult
to tie Uchiyama to the other five murders.

228
00:17:06,130 --> 00:17:09,007
You killed Ms. Morishita, didn't you?

229
00:17:11,969 --> 00:17:15,389
We found your DNA on her body,
you can't talk your way out of this.

230
00:17:15,472 --> 00:17:17,933
I have no intention of doing so.

231
00:17:19,601 --> 00:17:20,811
As you say,

232
00:17:21,395 --> 00:17:23,897
<i>I am the one who killed Morishita.</i>

233
00:17:27,693 --> 00:17:29,444
It wasn't just her, right?

234
00:17:30,404 --> 00:17:33,198
-The other five were also--
-That was me as well.

235
00:17:37,202 --> 00:17:42,124
Tamura, Shimizu,
Ikezawa, Konishi, Nomoto, all of them.

236
00:17:42,624 --> 00:17:43,917
I killed all of them.

237
00:17:46,545 --> 00:17:48,672
I thought I would let all who mocked me

238
00:17:48,755 --> 00:17:52,259
know just what type of person I really am.

239
00:18:01,435 --> 00:18:04,563
What about Shiramine 15 years ago?

240
00:18:10,194 --> 00:18:12,988
That was you too, wasn't it?

241
00:18:15,616 --> 00:18:17,367
No, it wasn't.

242
00:18:20,746 --> 00:18:22,372
That wasn't me.

243
00:18:32,591 --> 00:18:36,887
Uchiyama confessed to
all of the current murders.

244
00:18:36,970 --> 00:18:37,804
But,

245
00:18:38,972 --> 00:18:41,892
he flat out denies the Shiramine murders.

246
00:18:41,975 --> 00:18:43,352
In that case,

247
00:18:43,435 --> 00:18:46,313
Uchiyama wasn't the culprit
in Shiramine after all?

248
00:18:46,396 --> 00:18:47,231
No.

249
00:18:49,191 --> 00:18:51,568
He was definitely involved in it.

250
00:18:56,949 --> 00:18:58,033
In the first place,

251
00:18:58,116 --> 00:19:01,578
why would he admit to all five murders
when we had no evidence on him?

252
00:19:03,121 --> 00:19:04,873
After being released from prison,

253
00:19:04,957 --> 00:19:07,668
he had almost no money
and lived in terrible poverty.

254
00:19:08,168 --> 00:19:09,294
Probably,

255
00:19:10,128 --> 00:19:13,966
he wanted to get back at society
for looking down on him.

256
00:19:14,925 --> 00:19:16,802
So he confessed

257
00:19:17,844 --> 00:19:22,224
to show everyone that he was the one
who committed those murders.

258
00:19:22,307 --> 00:19:24,601
If that's his motive,

259
00:19:24,685 --> 00:19:28,146
why would he deny the Shiramine incident?

260
00:19:30,315 --> 00:19:32,109
<i>According to a friend at the police,</i>

261
00:19:32,192 --> 00:19:35,654
Uchiyama apparently does not admit
that he's involved in the Shiramine case.

262
00:19:35,737 --> 00:19:37,698
If he admits to the crime,

263
00:19:37,781 --> 00:19:39,533
things will get quite bad.

264
00:19:40,701 --> 00:19:43,745
Serizawa's family
will surely request a retrial.

265
00:19:44,246 --> 00:19:46,832
If a decision to commence
a retrial is issued,

266
00:19:47,332 --> 00:19:49,835
we will have to file an immediate appeal.

267
00:19:50,961 --> 00:19:52,587
What is an appeal?

268
00:19:52,671 --> 00:19:55,465
It means the prosecution
objects to the court's decision

269
00:19:55,549 --> 00:19:57,384
to start a retrial.

270
00:19:57,884 --> 00:20:01,346
If that happens, the retrial
will be contested all over again,

271
00:20:01,430 --> 00:20:04,182
and it will take several years
to reach a conclusion.

272
00:20:04,266 --> 00:20:05,851
That's terrible.

273
00:20:05,934 --> 00:20:07,185
That's so cruel.

274
00:20:08,312 --> 00:20:12,316
Mr. Serizawa has already had
15 years of his life stolen from him.

275
00:20:13,567 --> 00:20:15,944
<i>If the Shiramine charge is overturned,</i>

276
00:20:16,820 --> 00:20:20,157
both you and I will lose
our futures as prosecutors.

277
00:20:21,325 --> 00:20:22,576
It will be over.

278
00:20:25,245 --> 00:20:27,706
Our decision was one of justice.

279
00:20:30,751 --> 00:20:33,503
Our decision was one of justice…

280
00:20:44,723 --> 00:20:45,807
What's wrong?

281
00:20:45,891 --> 00:20:49,353
Mr. Yamazaki asked me to compile
these mental care reports

282
00:20:49,436 --> 00:20:51,521
we got from local municipalities.

283
00:20:52,314 --> 00:20:53,732
Mental care?

284
00:20:53,815 --> 00:20:56,902
Municipalities in areas where
major incidents or disasters occurred

285
00:20:56,985 --> 00:21:01,198
report to the government regarding their
response to residents' mental concerns.

286
00:21:03,075 --> 00:21:04,868
I heard there was even a police officer

287
00:21:04,951 --> 00:21:08,163
who committed suicide due to the stress
of the prolonged investigation.

288
00:21:09,081 --> 00:21:11,124
When did they start doing that?

289
00:21:12,167 --> 00:21:13,960
Over twenty years ago.

290
00:21:14,544 --> 00:21:16,797
The older ones haven't been digitized.

291
00:21:23,261 --> 00:21:26,473
PSYCHOLOGICAL EFFECTS
OF MAJOR EVENTS IN SHIRAMINE

292
00:21:47,744 --> 00:21:48,662
<i>Yes?</i>

293
00:21:48,745 --> 00:21:50,038
Sorry to disturb you.

294
00:21:50,122 --> 00:21:53,542
I am Kiryu from Medical Examiner Japan.

295
00:21:54,459 --> 00:21:58,380
Could I ask you some questions regarding
the Shiramine incident

296
00:21:58,463 --> 00:21:59,673
from 15 years ago?

297
00:22:00,424 --> 00:22:02,676
MAHO KIRYU

298
00:22:04,386 --> 00:22:05,303
Yes?

299
00:22:05,887 --> 00:22:08,223
There's something
that caught my attention.

300
00:22:08,306 --> 00:22:10,642
I'm in Shiramine.

301
00:22:11,226 --> 00:22:14,604
I want to tell you something, Doctor.

302
00:22:17,858 --> 00:22:20,527
Based on the evidence everyone gathered,

303
00:22:21,153 --> 00:22:23,071
we have filed a request for a retrial.

304
00:22:23,572 --> 00:22:24,739
But,

305
00:22:25,365 --> 00:22:28,118
the prosecution will undoubtedly

306
00:22:29,870 --> 00:22:31,872
try to buy time by filing an appeal.

307
00:22:35,917 --> 00:22:39,921
There is only one thing left
that we can do.

308
00:22:44,593 --> 00:22:46,803
A petition to the prosecution.

309
00:22:49,097 --> 00:22:52,350
We will go demand
that they do not file an appeal

310
00:22:52,434 --> 00:22:55,395
if the commencement
of the retrial is granted.

311
00:23:01,443 --> 00:23:02,360
Please.

312
00:23:03,820 --> 00:23:07,449
Will you all help me with this?

313
00:23:17,417 --> 00:23:19,836
PUBLIC PROSECUTION

314
00:23:36,978 --> 00:23:39,773
I have come here today with my lawyer

315
00:23:39,856 --> 00:23:45,070
to respectfully ask the prosecution
to refrain from filing an appeal.

316
00:23:45,695 --> 00:23:47,489
We are justice.

317
00:23:47,572 --> 00:23:52,160
We believed that the perpetrator
of the current serial murder case

318
00:23:52,244 --> 00:23:56,206
and the true culprit of the Shiramine
case were the same person.

319
00:23:56,289 --> 00:23:59,876
Amidst this, Koji Uchiyama was arrested.

320
00:24:00,627 --> 00:24:03,880
Koji Uchiyama denies involvement
in the Shiramine case.

321
00:24:03,964 --> 00:24:06,549
Without evidence,
that is just speculation.

322
00:24:06,633 --> 00:24:07,592
Indeed.

323
00:24:07,676 --> 00:24:11,554
Mr. Uchiyama denied involvement
in the Shiramine incident.

324
00:24:12,597 --> 00:24:16,476
Do you have any proof that I was
the culprit of that old case?

325
00:24:16,559 --> 00:24:18,061
If you do, please show me.

326
00:24:25,735 --> 00:24:27,237
You're right.

327
00:24:28,697 --> 00:24:31,783
There is no evidence whatsoever.

328
00:24:34,661 --> 00:24:38,039
Regarding the current
serial murder case, even…

329
00:24:38,748 --> 00:24:41,835
<i>in terms of evidence that you killed</i>
<i>the other five girls</i>

330
00:24:41,918 --> 00:24:43,962
besides Yukie Morishita.

331
00:24:45,213 --> 00:24:46,214
There is none.

332
00:24:46,798 --> 00:24:47,757
What?

333
00:24:48,591 --> 00:24:50,302
The only case with evidence

334
00:24:51,094 --> 00:24:55,015
is the murder of Yukie Morishita.

335
00:24:55,098 --> 00:25:00,103
You are not a serial killer.
You aren't anything at all.

336
00:25:01,521 --> 00:25:03,440
You boast about it,

337
00:25:03,523 --> 00:25:05,817
but you're nothing but a petty criminal.

338
00:25:07,819 --> 00:25:09,863
No, no, no, no!

339
00:25:10,989 --> 00:25:13,366
I killed the other five too.

340
00:25:13,450 --> 00:25:14,659
Really?

341
00:25:15,702 --> 00:25:18,413
Are you really that impressive a man?

342
00:25:19,289 --> 00:25:20,999
Too bad, though.

343
00:25:21,082 --> 00:25:23,376
There's no evidence.

344
00:25:29,758 --> 00:25:31,801
If there is any, please show me.

345
00:25:37,682 --> 00:25:39,184
I…

346
00:25:40,810 --> 00:25:43,521
killed six people
without getting caught by the police.

347
00:25:43,605 --> 00:25:44,856
I did it!

348
00:25:47,108 --> 00:25:49,611
I killed all three people

349
00:25:49,694 --> 00:25:51,988
from the Shiramine case, too!

350
00:25:55,492 --> 00:25:57,535
Uchiyama suddenly admitted

351
00:25:57,619 --> 00:26:00,413
to his involvement
in the Shiramine murders.

352
00:26:01,748 --> 00:26:02,749
However, this…

353
00:26:03,958 --> 00:26:05,168
was a lie.

354
00:26:06,294 --> 00:26:07,504
A lie?

355
00:26:09,005 --> 00:26:10,632
All three of them?

356
00:26:10,715 --> 00:26:12,050
That's right.

357
00:26:14,219 --> 00:26:17,430
That's a lie just to get
public attention, isn't it?

358
00:26:17,514 --> 00:26:18,473
No!

359
00:26:18,556 --> 00:26:19,599
Come on!

360
00:26:21,184 --> 00:26:26,231
The ones you killed were only the second
and third victim, right?

361
00:26:29,567 --> 00:26:31,152
The second and third?

362
00:26:31,653 --> 00:26:33,321
What are you talking about?

363
00:26:34,197 --> 00:26:39,077
We have done our investigation
under the assumption that the perpetrator

364
00:26:39,160 --> 00:26:43,665
of the current serial murder case
was the same as the Shiramine case.

365
00:26:46,376 --> 00:26:47,544
However,

366
00:26:48,545 --> 00:26:50,380
in the Shiramine incident,

367
00:26:50,880 --> 00:26:52,882
there were two perpetrators.

368
00:26:54,008 --> 00:26:55,135
Two?

369
00:26:56,594 --> 00:26:58,304
According to her family,

370
00:26:58,388 --> 00:27:01,015
<i>Yui Sato was being stalked.</i>

371
00:27:02,016 --> 00:27:07,480
We thought that the stalker might be
the culprit who murdered Sato.

372
00:27:07,564 --> 00:27:10,108
That's why it's Serizawa.

373
00:27:10,191 --> 00:27:13,736
Serizawa approached the victim
but was rejected,

374
00:27:13,820 --> 00:27:16,531
leading him to murder her
out of resentment.

375
00:27:16,614 --> 00:27:20,243
That is the story
fabricated by the prosecution.

376
00:27:20,326 --> 00:27:23,872
In reality, there was another stalker.

377
00:27:25,415 --> 00:27:27,876
Ms. Sato was troubled by the stalker,

378
00:27:27,959 --> 00:27:30,712
so her mother suggested
to consult the police.

379
00:27:31,963 --> 00:27:32,922
But,

380
00:27:33,756 --> 00:27:35,425
she didn't do so.

381
00:27:37,719 --> 00:27:41,222
Why didn't Yui Sato consult the police?

382
00:27:42,015 --> 00:27:44,851
It wasn't to avoid causing trouble
within her family,

383
00:27:45,560 --> 00:27:48,313
nor because she disliked
making a big deal.

384
00:27:49,481 --> 00:27:51,191
It was because that stalker

385
00:27:52,108 --> 00:27:54,194
was a police officer.

386
00:27:55,653 --> 00:27:57,530
What grounds do you have for saying that?

387
00:27:57,614 --> 00:27:59,657
No such testimony has come from anywhere.

388
00:27:59,741 --> 00:28:02,577
In fact, Serizawa has admitted
to the stalking behavior.

389
00:28:02,660 --> 00:28:05,455
In Shiramine at the time,
there was a rumor

390
00:28:05,538 --> 00:28:09,459
that two people had committed suicide
in connection with the murder.

391
00:28:10,335 --> 00:28:13,463
One was Yui Sato's boyfriend, Sho Mizuta.

392
00:28:13,546 --> 00:28:16,925
It was said that he committed suicide
due to the shock of losing her.

393
00:28:17,008 --> 00:28:19,093
The other was a police officer,

394
00:28:19,177 --> 00:28:22,931
who supposedly chose death due to
the stress of the prolonged investigation.

395
00:28:23,014 --> 00:28:24,474
<i>Following the incident,</i>

396
00:28:24,557 --> 00:28:28,186
<i>Shiramine compiled a report</i>
<i>on the consultation status and responses,</i>

397
00:28:28,269 --> 00:28:30,647
<i>and submitted it to the MHLW.</i>

398
00:28:30,730 --> 00:28:32,649
<i>In that report,</i>

399
00:28:32,732 --> 00:28:36,653
<i>it was written that Sho Mizuta, who worked</i>
<i>at the Shiramine Police Station,</i>

400
00:28:36,736 --> 00:28:40,281
<i>was found hanging at his home.</i>

401
00:28:41,574 --> 00:28:42,951
In other words,

402
00:28:43,743 --> 00:28:50,083
Yui Sato's boyfriend and Sho Mizuta,
the police officer who committed suicide,

403
00:28:51,376 --> 00:28:53,336
were in fact the same person.

404
00:28:57,799 --> 00:28:59,884
So what if they are the same person?

405
00:29:00,468 --> 00:29:03,763
That doesn't constitute proof
that he murdered Yui Sato.

406
00:29:04,430 --> 00:29:05,974
We do have proof.

407
00:29:11,896 --> 00:29:13,022
Mr. and Mrs. Mizuta.

408
00:29:14,357 --> 00:29:15,900
I understand

409
00:29:15,984 --> 00:29:19,028
that you have been suffering
for a long time over your son.

410
00:29:19,112 --> 00:29:20,196
But,

411
00:29:21,322 --> 00:29:25,118
both Shinichi Serizawa
and his older sister

412
00:29:25,201 --> 00:29:27,495
have also been suffering for 15 years.

413
00:29:30,874 --> 00:29:32,041
Please…

414
00:29:33,710 --> 00:29:36,379
Would you tell me the truth?

415
00:29:43,887 --> 00:29:45,013
We are

416
00:29:45,680 --> 00:29:48,516
so sorry.

417
00:29:51,060 --> 00:29:53,021
Sho Mizuta's parents

418
00:29:54,105 --> 00:29:56,482
have admitted to their son's crime.

419
00:30:06,701 --> 00:30:10,079
Two months before the incident,
Yui Sato told Mizuta

420
00:30:10,914 --> 00:30:13,750
that she wanted to break up.

421
00:30:13,833 --> 00:30:17,629
Unable to accept it,
he kept pressing her to get back together.

422
00:30:18,922 --> 00:30:21,341
However, in the end,

423
00:30:22,050 --> 00:30:24,802
that gradually turned
into him stalking her.

424
00:30:25,511 --> 00:30:27,221
On the night of the incident,

425
00:30:28,556 --> 00:30:32,644
Mizuta waited for Sato
as she finished her part-time job

426
00:30:32,727 --> 00:30:34,312
and murdered her.

427
00:30:34,395 --> 00:30:38,024
He told his parents this while crying.

428
00:30:39,442 --> 00:30:40,401
Then,

429
00:30:40,860 --> 00:30:43,154
when his parents left him alone for a bit,

430
00:30:44,364 --> 00:30:46,741
he had taken his own life.

431
00:30:49,494 --> 00:30:51,746
The one who murdered Yui Sato

432
00:30:52,246 --> 00:30:53,915
was Sho Mizuta.

433
00:30:55,124 --> 00:30:57,752
This fact has been hidden

434
00:30:58,586 --> 00:31:01,047
by his parents for 15 years.

435
00:31:02,048 --> 00:31:03,633
That is just…

436
00:31:05,343 --> 00:31:08,304
the parents' delusion.

437
00:31:08,388 --> 00:31:11,224
There is no objective evidence
that he did it--

438
00:31:13,601 --> 00:31:17,814
This is his belt that we borrowed
from Mizuta's parents' home.

439
00:31:18,648 --> 00:31:24,529
This belt perfectly matches the
strangulation marks on Yui Sato's neck.

440
00:31:25,196 --> 00:31:28,157
However, Professor Kujo's expert opinion

441
00:31:28,241 --> 00:31:32,662
concluded that the murder weapon
was consistent with Serizawa's belt.

442
00:31:32,745 --> 00:31:34,539
Are you saying he was mistaken?

443
00:31:34,622 --> 00:31:39,002
"Consistent" and "matching" sound similar,
but they are different.

444
00:31:39,877 --> 00:31:42,755
In the sense that she was strangled
with a leather strap,

445
00:31:42,839 --> 00:31:44,465
it is indeed consistent.

446
00:31:45,675 --> 00:31:47,176
But Mizuta's belt

447
00:31:47,885 --> 00:31:52,473
is a perfect match with
the width of the strangulation marks.

448
00:31:57,186 --> 00:32:02,025
In other words, the murders committed
by Sho Mizuta and Koji Uchiyama

449
00:32:02,108 --> 00:32:05,653
were entirely separate crimes, and yet

450
00:32:05,737 --> 00:32:08,948
they were treated
as a single serial murder case.

451
00:32:09,032 --> 00:32:11,868
That was the reality
of the Shiramine case.

452
00:32:14,203 --> 00:32:17,623
Even though there were two killers,
the police at the time

453
00:32:17,707 --> 00:32:20,752
assumed that there was only one culprit.

454
00:32:20,835 --> 00:32:22,128
That's why

455
00:32:22,628 --> 00:32:25,048
the investigation was
full of contradictions

456
00:32:25,548 --> 00:32:28,551
and nobody could grasp
the full scope of the case.

457
00:32:29,969 --> 00:32:31,387
And this was exactly

458
00:32:32,055 --> 00:32:35,141
what Koji Uchiyama was aiming for.

459
00:32:35,725 --> 00:32:38,186
As an informant,

460
00:32:39,353 --> 00:32:42,523
you knew that the police
were unable to name a suspect

461
00:32:42,607 --> 00:32:47,570
in the murder of Yui Sato,
and that the scene was in chaos.

462
00:32:48,154 --> 00:32:49,864
In the midst of that,

463
00:32:50,865 --> 00:32:56,412
having a financial dispute
with the second female victim,

464
00:32:57,455 --> 00:33:04,128
you copied the first murder
to make your own murder blend into it.

465
00:33:05,922 --> 00:33:06,964
And,

466
00:33:08,299 --> 00:33:12,011
so that your existence wouldn't be traced
through the victim's acquaintances,

467
00:33:12,095 --> 00:33:14,722
you chose a woman
with absolutely no connection to you

468
00:33:14,806 --> 00:33:16,766
and killed her as the third victim.

469
00:33:18,059 --> 00:33:22,313
The reason you didn't admit
to the Shiramine incident was because…

470
00:33:27,026 --> 00:33:28,611
you were afraid

471
00:33:29,612 --> 00:33:33,866
it would be revealed that you were just

472
00:33:35,284 --> 00:33:39,413
a small-time criminal
who jumped on someone else's murder.

473
00:33:41,290 --> 00:33:43,626
Just as Uchiyama planned,

474
00:33:44,627 --> 00:33:46,796
the police reached a dead end.

475
00:33:46,879 --> 00:33:48,506
As a result of their impatience,

476
00:33:48,589 --> 00:33:52,593
they framed Mr. Serizawa as the culprit
to settle the case.

477
00:33:53,177 --> 00:33:55,721
To turn Mr. Serizawa into the culprit,

478
00:33:55,805 --> 00:33:59,976
they chose to ignore
the inconvenient contradictions.

479
00:34:00,685 --> 00:34:01,936
And that…

480
00:34:04,147 --> 00:34:06,357
applies to the past version of me as well.

481
00:34:08,818 --> 00:34:14,031
Despite noticing a contradiction
in Professor Kujo's medical report,

482
00:34:15,199 --> 00:34:16,951
I gave up on blowing the whistle

483
00:34:17,493 --> 00:34:18,911
and ran away.

484
00:34:21,706 --> 00:34:22,999
Because of that,

485
00:34:23,583 --> 00:34:26,586
15 years were taken away from Mr. Serizawa

486
00:34:27,795 --> 00:34:30,381
and from his family.

487
00:34:36,888 --> 00:34:41,184
We cannot give back the time they've lost.

488
00:34:42,351 --> 00:34:46,522
That's why we must at least
not take away the opportunity

489
00:34:47,440 --> 00:34:49,442
for Mr. Serizawa and his family

490
00:34:50,026 --> 00:34:52,069
to reclaim their honor.

491
00:35:07,835 --> 00:35:08,961
Please,

492
00:35:09,837 --> 00:35:11,589
make a wise decision.

493
00:35:12,131 --> 00:35:13,216
Please.

494
00:35:24,769 --> 00:35:26,562
I understand what you are saying.

495
00:35:26,646 --> 00:35:27,730
However,

496
00:35:27,813 --> 00:35:33,236
an appeal is a legitimate procedure
granted to the prosecution.

497
00:35:34,820 --> 00:35:37,281
In order to seek a careful examination,

498
00:35:38,032 --> 00:35:40,326
the policy to file an appeal--

499
00:35:59,053 --> 00:36:00,972
Ota! What are you doing?

500
00:36:01,681 --> 00:36:02,556
Stop it!

501
00:36:07,436 --> 00:36:10,439
The responsibility
for taking 15 years from Mr. Serizawa

502
00:36:11,565 --> 00:36:12,942
lies with us.

503
00:36:17,238 --> 00:36:18,322
I am deeply…

504
00:36:22,034 --> 00:36:23,828
deeply sorry.

505
00:37:56,754 --> 00:37:57,922
Sis…

506
00:38:19,193 --> 00:38:20,444
Welcome back.

507
00:38:28,911 --> 00:38:29,995
Yes.

508
00:39:04,238 --> 00:39:05,322
Ms. Kiryu.

509
00:39:07,158 --> 00:39:08,576
Thank you.

510
00:39:12,705 --> 00:39:13,831
Ever since…

511
00:39:16,959 --> 00:39:20,254
Ever since I was a child,

512
00:39:20,754 --> 00:39:24,383
if something in front of me didn't add up,
I couldn't just leave it alone.

513
00:39:25,968 --> 00:39:30,222
Revealing the truth behind things
was my way to cope

514
00:39:30,890 --> 00:39:34,101
and the only place I belonged.

515
00:39:37,771 --> 00:39:39,190
The Shiramine case

516
00:39:40,065 --> 00:39:43,486
was the only contradiction in my life

517
00:39:44,278 --> 00:39:46,572
that I turned my eyes away from.

518
00:39:47,907 --> 00:39:50,701
The reason I was obsessed
with the Shiramine incident…

519
00:39:53,454 --> 00:39:56,123
may not have been to save Mr. Serizawa.

520
00:39:57,291 --> 00:40:00,544
I think it may have been

521
00:40:01,420 --> 00:40:02,796
to save my past self.

522
00:40:09,053 --> 00:40:12,932
I want to thank you as well.

523
00:40:16,101 --> 00:40:19,188
I might have been lacking in many ways.

524
00:40:20,439 --> 00:40:21,565
All this time,

525
00:40:22,107 --> 00:40:26,278
I've always intended to face
the "loved ones" in my own way.

526
00:40:29,281 --> 00:40:32,993
I was able to see many things

527
00:40:33,577 --> 00:40:35,538
I had never seen before.

528
00:40:40,417 --> 00:40:41,961
The days I spent…

529
00:40:46,757 --> 00:40:48,551
with everyone at the MEJ…

530
00:40:50,761 --> 00:40:53,013
are something I will always treasure.

531
00:40:57,893 --> 00:40:58,936
Doctor.

532
00:41:00,229 --> 00:41:01,689
Thank you.

533
00:41:08,654 --> 00:41:09,655
Sure.

534
00:41:38,309 --> 00:41:39,685
<i>Now for the next story.</i>

535
00:41:39,768 --> 00:41:41,895
<i>In the retrial for the case</i>
<i>of a triple murder</i>

536
00:41:41,979 --> 00:41:44,607
<i>that happened in Shiramine 16 years ago,</i>

537
00:41:44,690 --> 00:41:47,067
<i>the Tokyo District Court handed down</i>

538
00:41:47,151 --> 00:41:49,903
<i>a not guilty verdict to Shinichi Serizawa,</i>

539
00:41:49,987 --> 00:41:51,989
<i>who was formerly on death row.</i>

540
00:41:55,826 --> 00:41:59,913
<i>Following this, Shinichi Serizawa</i>
<i>and his older sister, Akiko,</i>

541
00:41:59,997 --> 00:42:02,249
<i>held a press conference in Tokyo.</i>

542
00:42:03,417 --> 00:42:06,003
<i>Thanks to the support of so many people,</i>

543
00:42:06,086 --> 00:42:09,298
<i>we were able to get to this day.</i>

544
00:42:10,341 --> 00:42:13,010
<i>Thank you so very much.</i>

545
00:42:13,636 --> 00:42:14,637
Ms. Dojima!

546
00:42:14,720 --> 00:42:16,722
We found a witness!

547
00:42:17,431 --> 00:42:18,807
I'll go talk to them.

548
00:42:18,891 --> 00:42:19,892
Yes, ma'am!

549
00:42:19,975 --> 00:42:22,102
<i>We were able to keep going</i>

550
00:42:22,770 --> 00:42:24,229
<i>without giving up,</i>

551
00:42:24,313 --> 00:42:26,607
<i>because of the people</i>
<i>who stood by our side.</i>

552
00:42:28,067 --> 00:42:31,153
<i>Now, my younger brother and I</i>

553
00:42:32,237 --> 00:42:37,284
<i>would like to live in peace,</i>
<i>and treasure the time we have.</i>

554
00:42:38,285 --> 00:42:41,288
<i>There were many times, until now,</i>

555
00:42:42,623 --> 00:42:45,709
<i>when I thought it was over.</i>

556
00:42:48,921 --> 00:42:49,838
<i>But…</i>

557
00:42:52,633 --> 00:42:53,467
<i>my sister</i>

558
00:42:54,802 --> 00:42:58,555
<i>believed in me to the very end.</i>

559
00:42:58,639 --> 00:42:59,682
<i>I am so grateful.</i>

560
00:42:59,765 --> 00:43:01,058
-Kiryu!
-Yes?

561
00:43:01,141 --> 00:43:02,434
The proposal you submitted

562
00:43:02,518 --> 00:43:05,646
for the new cause-of-death
investigation system was excellent.

563
00:43:05,729 --> 00:43:06,855
Can you proceed with this?

564
00:43:07,773 --> 00:43:09,108
Thank you very much.

565
00:43:12,027 --> 00:43:13,070
That's great.

566
00:43:13,654 --> 00:43:14,780
Oh, yes.

567
00:43:20,911 --> 00:43:22,413
MAHO KIRYU

568
00:43:34,049 --> 00:43:37,010
<i>Now, with this verdict,</i>
<i>Serizawa and his family</i>

569
00:43:37,094 --> 00:43:40,597
<i>will finally be able</i>
<i>to take a new step forward.</i>

570
00:43:41,098 --> 00:43:43,517
<i>The prosecution</i>
<i>will not be submitting an appeal,</i>

571
00:43:43,600 --> 00:43:46,061
<i>and apologized to Serizawa</i>
<i>and his family, saying,</i>

572
00:43:46,145 --> 00:43:49,857
<i>"We have caused you many years of pain."</i>

573
00:44:09,918 --> 00:44:12,963
Subtitle translation by: Maslin F.

